dismissalText.commentary: Jacob Oram c Maharoof b Dilshan 31 (45b 0x4 1x6 52m) SR: 68.88

dismissalComment.html: Dilshan has the revenge. Oram falls. He came down the track, Dilshan dragged back the length, Oram went through with his lofted drive, but the bottom-hand came off the handle and the ball went high up in the air towards long-on. It hung in the air for a long time and then swirled down, Maharoof went forward, then to his left, then to his right as the ball kept swirling and lunged to his left to hold on to it. Mahela is first to rush across to give Mahroof a big hug.

dismissalComment.html: Murali removes McMillan. Tossed-up, on the middle stump line, on a length, McMillan tries to sweep, the ball turns in and bounces, gets a top-edge and bobs away to the left of short fine-leg fielder. Sri Lanka are on top here. And this is Murali's second over. Eight more to tackle. NZ in big trouble.

headshotImage.caption: BB McCullum headshot
headshotImage.longCaption: BB McCullum headshot

dismissalComment.html: McCullum goes cheaply. From round the stumps, it landed on the middle and leg stump line, turns in slightly, McCullum pushes at it, the bat comes outside the line, the ball thuds into the pad. Murali turns around and appeals. No luck. The ball bobs off the pad to left of silly-point where Arnold grabs it. They appeal for a catch and it's given. McCullum is unhappy. As he walks past Rauf, he asks him something and shakes his head at the response. Confirmation comes from the umpire that it was given LBW He was struck in front of leg and middle.

commentPreTextItems.html: 3rd Powerplay is on! Will Sangakkara be tempted now?

commentTextItems.html: He does it! It was full and outside leg, Sangakkara, who has maintained a monk like patience today, swings it past the short fine-leg fielder.

commentPostTextItems.html: Pretty clinical from Sri Lanka. No drama, no urge to indulge in showmanship. No frantic hitting. There was no need. 220 was not a stiff target and they jogged home.  Two more points. New Zealand have tasted defeat for the first time in the tournament.

Ranatunga, sitting in a television studio,  is not quite thrilled with the way SL approached the chase. " I am a bit disappointed with the way they played. They should have struck to their usual aggressive game." He would have liked to see the likes of Jayasuriya playing more aggressively. Well.... you can't please everyone.

Sangakkara had said on the eve of the game: "Most of the times we've gone wrong, we've tried to change our game, but we've realised that's a bit foolish. When we won the World Cup we played a unique brand of cricket and that's how we play now against any side"
I guess they would have played that way but here they were chasing a small target and  must have felt there was no need to up the ante.
This is Sriram Veera, signing off. Adios.

commentTextItems.html: McCullum shouts 'Catch' as Sangakkara drives on the up and it flies over the outstretched hands of Oram.

dismissalText.commentary: Sanath Jayasuriya c †McCullum b Oram 64 (80b 5x4 1x6 111m) SR: 80

dismissalComment.html: Jayasuriya falls. McCullum can finally smile. Landed on a length, well outside off stump, Jayasuriya tries to chop it down to third man, gets a bottom-edge and McCullum does well to snap it up. Good knock from Jayasuriya; he has laid a nice platform for the other batsmen.

dismissalText.commentary: Mahela Jayawardene c sub (HJH Marshall) b Vettori 15 (16b 2x4 0x6 21m) SR: 93.75

dismissalComment.html: short and on the stumps, Jayawardene sees it a touch late and decides to climb into the pull shot anyway, it's hit reasonably hard but not hard enough or high enough to get past the substitute fielder Hamish Marshall at midwicket. He doesn't drop those and Jaywardene kicks himself all the way back to the pavilion for giving his wicket away so softly just when Sri Lanka were coasting along. Big wicket for New Zealand this!

dismissalText.commentary: Chamara Silva c Bond b Vettori 23 (34b 4x4 0x6 33m) SR: 67.64

dismissalComment.html: Done in the flight. Vettori tossed it up, slow in the air, Silva came down the track and is made to wait a touch and he lofts it straight to long-off. Sangakkara says something to him as he walks past. Maybe he was admonishing him or may be he was asking for some special item to be ordered for dinner.  I think it was something about the rash stroke.
